Introductory/Descriptive Reports:

1.

How have U.S. vaccination rates varied over time?

library(ggplot2)

usvacc <- as.data.frame(usVaccines)
#length(x$DTP1) # 38
usvacc$year <- c(1980:2017)

ggplot(data = usvacc) + 
  geom_line(aes(x = usvacc$year, y = usvacc$DTP1, colour = "DTP1")) + 
  geom_line(aes(x = usvacc$year, y = usvacc$HepB_BD, colour = "HepB_BD")) +
  geom_line(aes(x = usvacc$year, y = usvacc$Pol3, colour = "Pol3")) +
  geom_line(aes(x = usvacc$year, y = usvacc$Hib3, colour = "Hib3")) +
  geom_line(aes(x = usvacc$year, y = usvacc$MCV1, colour = "MCV1")) + 
  scale_color_manual(name = "Vacinations", values = c("DTP1" = 'red',
                                                      "HepB_BD" = 'orange',
                                                      "Pol3" = 'purple',
                                                      "Hib3" = 'blue',
                                                      "MCV1" = 'darkgreen')) +
  xlab("Year") + 
  ylab("Vaccination rate (%)") + 
  ggtitle("Figure 1. Vaccination Rates (US): 1980 - 2017")

# Overall, we have seen a general rise in vaccination rates from 1980 - 2017.  Pol3 saw the largest change (increase) in vaccinations over time (<10% to ~67%), while the other vaccines saw overall unchanging rates, except for a time between 1985 and 1990, where all vaccines (minus DTP1) saw a significant dip in vaccination rates); see Figure 1.

Are vaccination rates increasing or decreasing?

# it appears that all vaccines, minus HepB_BD, saw an increasing trend from 1980 to ~1990, then leveled off for the most part.  HepB_BD, on the other hand, has seen an upward trend all the way from 1990 to the end of the time series in the figure above.

Which vaccination has the highest rate at the conclusion of the time series?

# From Figure 1., above, we can see that DTP1 has the highest vaccination rate at the end of the time series.

Which vaccination has the lowest rate at the conclusion of the time series?

# From Figure 1., above, we can see that HepB_BD has the lowest vaccination rate at the end of the time series.

Which vaccine has the greatest volatility?

library(tseries)

plot(diff(usVaccines))

# From the plot above, we can see that HepB_BD had the highest (most frequent) volatility across the time series.  Each of the other vaccines had sharp falls and rises in rates, but not as frequently.

What proportion of public schools reported vaccination data?

library(tidyverse)

allreports <- as.data.frame(allSchoolsReportStatus)

allreports_public <- allreports %>%
  filter(.$pubpriv == "PUBLIC")

public_Y_perc <- length(allreports_public$reported[allreports_public$reported == "Y"]) / length(allreports_public$reported)
public_N_perc <- length(allreports_public$reported[allreports_public$reported == "N"]) / length(allreports_public$reported)

Was there any credible difference in overall reporting proportions between public and private schools?

library(plyr)
library(BEST)

allreports_coded <- allreports

allreports_coded$reported <- revalue(allreports_coded$reported, c("Y"=1))
allreports_coded$reported <- revalue(allreports_coded$reported, c("N"=0))

allreports_coded_public <- allreports_coded %>%
  filter(.$pubpriv == "PUBLIC")

allreports_coded_private <- allreports_coded %>%
  filter(.$pubpriv == "PRIVATE")

t.test(as.numeric(allreports_coded_public$reported), as.numeric(allreports_coded_private$reported))
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  as.numeric(allreports_coded_public$reported) and as.numeric(allreports_coded_private$reported)
## t = 13.944, df = 1835.6, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1091376 0.1448623
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 0.9741800 0.8471801
# From the t-test results above (comparing the Y/N results of the public/private schools), we can reject the null hypothesis (the difference in reporting between the two types of schools is statistically significant/not zero); t = 13.944; p < 0.001.

3.

What are 2013 vaccination rates for individual vaccines (i.e., DOT, Polio, MMR, and HepB) in California public schools? How do these rates for individual vaccines in California districts compare with overall US vaccination rates (make an informal comparison to the final observations in the time series)?

# create a data frame that contains all the necessary data:

DTP2013_CA_perc <- sum(districts$Enrolled - ((districts$WithoutDTP/100) * districts$Enrolled)) / sum(districts$Enrolled)
DTP2013_US_perc <- usvacc$DTP1[usvacc$year == 2013]/100

Polio2013_CA_perc <- sum(districts$Enrolled - ((districts$WithoutPolio/100) * districts$Enrolled)) / sum(districts$Enrolled)
Polio2013_US_perc <- usvacc$Pol3[usvacc$year == 2013]/100

MMR2013_CA_perc <- sum(districts$Enrolled - ((districts$WithoutMMR/100) * districts$Enrolled)) / sum(districts$Enrolled)
MMR2013_US_perc <- usvacc$MCV1[usvacc$year == 2013]/100

HepB2013_CA_perc <- sum(districts$Enrolled - ((districts$WithoutHepB/100) * districts$Enrolled)) / sum(districts$Enrolled)
HepB2013_US_perc <- usvacc$HepB_BD[usvacc$year == 2013]/100

vaccs <- c("DTP", "Polio", "MMR", "HepB")
CA <- c(DTP2013_CA_perc,Polio2013_CA_perc,MMR2013_CA_perc,HepB2013_CA_perc)
US <- c(DTP2013_US_perc,Polio2013_US_perc,MMR2013_US_perc,HepB2013_US_perc)

dfA <- data.frame(vaccs, CA, US)
dfA
##   vaccs        CA   US
## 1   DTP 0.9224792 0.98
## 2 Polio 0.9274081 0.93
## 3   MMR 0.9249139 0.92
## 4  HepB 0.9487756 0.74
# From the data frame outlined above, we can see the rates for individual vaccines as well as how those rates compared to the overall US vaccination rates for those same vaccines.  Overall, in 2013, California schools were below the US average vaccination rate for DTP and Polio, but were above the US average in MMR and HepB.

# Note:  I know that the question stated to make an 'informal' comparison to the time series, but I believe that this provides a clearer picture, as it directly compares both groups' rates during the same year.

# throw in bar chart that shows US2013 vs. US2017

dfA_2 <- dfA %>%
  gather(Group, Perc, -vaccs) %>%
  mutate(vaccs = factor(vaccs, levels = c("DTP", "Polio", "MMR", "HepB"))) %>%
  arrange(vaccs)

ggplot(data = dfA_2) + 
  geom_bar(aes(x = vaccs,
               y = Perc,
               fill = Group,
               color = Group),
           stat = 'identity',
           position = position_dodge()) + 
  xlab("Vaccine") + 
  ylab("Vaccination Rate") + 
  ggtitle("Figure 3 - 2013 Vaccination Rates: California vs. United States")

Among districts, how are the vaccination rates for individual vaccines related? In other words, if students are missing one vaccine are they missing all of the others?

library(car)

cor(districts[, 2:6])
##              WithoutDTP WithoutPolio WithoutMMR WithoutHepB PctUpToDate
## WithoutDTP    1.0000000    0.9814507  0.9768910   0.8882872  -0.9579712
## WithoutPolio  0.9814507    1.0000000  0.9649482   0.9034700  -0.9379057
## WithoutMMR    0.9768910    0.9649482  1.0000000   0.8901950  -0.9660567
## WithoutHepB   0.8882872    0.9034700  0.8901950   1.0000000  -0.8401573
## PctUpToDate  -0.9579712   -0.9379057 -0.9660567  -0.8401573   1.0000000
# I do not believe that you can answer this question with just the vaccination data; from the correlation table above, we can infer that if a student does not have a particular vaccine, the `PctUpToDate` rate will go down, but we cannot infer if they are missing all the other vaccines.

8.

What’s the big picture, based on all of the foregoing analyses? The staff member in the state legislator’s office is interested to know how to allocate financial assistance to school districts to improve both their vaccination rates and their reporting compliance. What have you learned from the data and analyses that might inform this question?




Techincal Report.

Good afternoon [INSERT LEGISLATOR NAME],

Below is my technical analysis based on questions submitted and data related to allocating financial assistance to schools in order to improve vaccination rates and reporting:

Analysis of available data.

First, we took a look at the overall vaccination rates in the United States for the selected vaccinations over the past thirty years, just to get a feel for the trend. See Figure 1.



From Figure 1, we can see that there has been significant improvement across the U.S. in terms of vaccination rates for these specific vaccinations. However, we are more concerned at this time with the rates in the school districts of California. To start on this analysis, we need to differentiate between the public and private schools. See Figure 2.




From Figures 2.1 and 2.2 above, we can see that public schools have a significantly higher reporting rate (~97.4%) than private schools (~84.7%) in California. Also, California as a whole appears to be lacking in the vaccination rates in DTP and Polio (see Figure 3.). There was a significant difference found in the mean reporting rates between public and private schools (t = 13.944, p < 0.001) (see Figure 4.)



Figure 4 - Results of t-test: Differences between public and private school vaccination reporting.


In the case of reporting, we may want to allocated funds to reaching out to the private schools to see why they are lacking in reporting compared to their public counter parts. For the rest of this report, we will be focusing on all districts and the factors that may lead to lower reporting and vaccination rates.

The first specific question that we talked with this analysis is which factors predict whether or not a district’s reporting was complete (regardless of public/private status). We looked at the following variables as predictors of a district completing its reporting, starting with a binomial regression (generalized linear model). See Figure 5:

  • PctChildPoverty : Percentage of children in the district living below the poverty line
  • PctFreeMeal : Percentage of children in the district eligible for free student meals
  • PctFamilyPoverty : Percentage of families in the district living below the poverty line
  • Enrolled : Total number of enrolled students in the district
  • TotalSchools : Total number of different schools in the district


Figure 5 - Results of generalized linear model regression (binomial): predictors of district vaccination reporting completion


An analysis using A Bayesian logit model was also performed in order to get a sense of the predicted population (see Figure 6).


Figure 6 - Plots of Bayesian logit model (binomial): predictors of district vaccination reporting completion


From Figures 5 and 6 above, we can see that only the variables of Enrolled (t = 3.088, p < 0.01) and TotalSchools (t = -3.509, p < 0.001) were possible viable predictors of vaccination report completion for the sample and predicted population. However, when a test for multicollinearity was performed, these variables each reported a score of ~ 48 (much higher than the 1-5 range for them to be considered a viable predictor). See Figure 7.


Figure 7 - Results of multicollinearity test (vif()) for predictors of district vaccination report completion


The second specific question we pursued was which factors predicted the percentage of all enrolled students with completely up-to-date vaccine. We used the same approach as the previous question, starting with a general liner model and then confirming with a Bayesian analysis. We looked at the same variables as predictors from the previous question (See Figure 8.1):


Figure 8.1 - Results of generalized linear model for predictors of percentage of students with completely up-to-date vaccine

Here, we can see what all variables included in this regression analysis (except for PctChildPoverty), appear to be viable cadidates for prediction of students being up-to-date on all vaccines. To confirm this, we turn to the Bayesian analysis (see Figure 8.2)


Figure 8.2 - Results of Bayesian analysis for predictors of percentage of students with completely up-to-date vaccine


In the Bayesian analysis, we see that all of the histograms of the frequencies of percentages (minus PctChildPoverty) do not include zero in the 95% HDI; this indicates that those variables would be good candidates for predicting up-to-date vaccination rates. However, we again turn to the multicollinearity test to check how viable these predictors are (See figure 9):


Figure 9 - Results of multicollinearity test for predictors of percentage of students with completely up-to-date vaccine

Again, we see that the Enrolled and TotalSchools variables fail the multicollinearity test, leaving PctFreeMeal and PctFamilyPoverty as the last-standing viable predictors of students being completely up-to-date on their vaccines.

Recommendations.

From the analyses performed above, we would recommend focusing funds towards assisting those families in the district that are living below the poverty line (as this was the only viable predictor of students not having up-to-date vaccines). Further data is needed to identify the specific reasons why these families fall short on vaccination rates.

Also, even though the variables concerning the total number of students enrolled in a district and the number of schools in a district failed collinearity tests and may not be statistically significant, it may be worth investigating if districts are having issues with keeping up with sheer numbers of students.
